Energy and the Environment

On June 25, 2013, President Obama addressed an audience at Georgetown University on the subject of the environment. Briefly mentioning how weather extremes in recorded history had occurred over the course of the previous fifteen years, he focused on the problem of global warming:

Last year, temperatures in some areas of the ocean reached record highs, and ice in the Arctic shrank to its smallest size on record—faster than most models had predicted it would. These are facts.

—President Obama, Georgetown University, June 25, 2013

Coastal areas of the United States will be under threat, if, as many scientists predict, the warming of the atmosphere leads to a rise in sea levels. In low-lying areas of Florida, high tides are already leading to overflowing of storm drains or inundating sections of city streets. With Florida heavily dependent on tourism, an increase in sea levels could seriously affect the state’s economy. In Hawaii, the erosion of long-term sea walls, which have been rising for the last 100 years, may accelerate, threatening urban areas.

Global warming has implications far beyond rising seas. The Environmental Protection Agency warns that in Alaska, where the increase in temperature has been more than twice the average increase in the rest of the United States, forest fires are increasing, while sea ice is decreasing. The warming of the atmosphere, and permafrost is thawing. This melting permafrost, which may lead to ground subsidence, is a direct threat to transportation systems and buildings.

Legislating to Protect the Environment

In recent years, environmental issues have aroused political controversy. Some deny that our planet is becoming warmer and oppose global warming agreements on the grounds that global warming may not be caused by humans, or deny that such warming is the product of human activity. Others do not want the government to interfere with business and would oppose laws that might slow economic growth by requiring American government to move forcefully to pass strict and effective environmental regulations.

While past federal government legislation to further conserve and protect the nation’s water has failed in Congress, states have enacted their own legislation, protecting rivers, bays, lakes, and wetlands. In addition, recent national energy and environmental legislation is having a positive impact on the nation’s industries.

During the Obama administration, regulations designed to limit emissions from power plants, prompting many coal industry officials to condemn the new laws. Others were concerned that the years of planning needed to develop environmental regulations for many types of energy use would discourage investment in renewable energy. When Donald Trump became president, he often promised to roll back what he considered the overregulation of the environment. At the same time, the government eliminated incentives created by previous administrations that sought to move America away from heavy emphasis on coal and oil.

The Environment and Local Economies

Environmental issues have become increasingly important at the local level since the 1970s. Residents of Beverly Hills, California, for example, succeeded in getting a nearby oil company to curb air pollution that was drifting over their neighborhood. Residents of many communities have opposed zoning variances that would have allowed environmentally hazardous facilities such as landfills, garbage dumps, and nuclear power plants to be placed near their homes.
